<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-05-04T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-05-04T03:00:00-05:00" n="698" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d698">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/1500: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Tenney</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-05-04T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">May 4,
                                            1920—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received May 4—9:52
                                    a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>100. Referring to Department’s telegram of April 24, 2 p.m. After a
                                consultation with the Premier and with Russo-Asiatic Bank officials
                                and Horvat, I conclude that China does not intend to disregard
                                former agreement with Russia though ambitious to make Chinese
                                influence more effective in the management of Chinese Eastern
                                Railway.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Tenney</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>